LeetCode 1594 · Maximum Non-Negative Product in a Matrix

🧠 Intuition
When you walk from top-left to bottom-right, you can only go right or down. The tricky part? Multiplying two negatives gives a positive — so the minimum (most negative) product at any cell might become the maximum if the next cell is also negative.
That's the core insight: track both the max and min product at every cell simultaneously.

🔑 Key Observation
At each cell (i, j), the new product depends on grid[i][j]:

If grid[i][j] > 0 → max stays max, min stays min
If grid[i][j] < 0 → max and min flip! (negative × negative = positive)
If grid[i][j] == 0 → everything resets to 0

So we must always carry both max and min forward.

🧩 Approach — DP with (max, min) pairs
Define:

maxDp[i][j] = maximum product of any path reaching (i, j)
minDp[i][j] = minimum product of any path reaching (i, j)

Transitions:
From top (i-1, j) and left (i, j-1), multiply current cell value and take:
maxDp[i][j] = max(maxDp[i-1][j] * val, minDp[i-1][j] * val,
                   maxDp[i][j-1] * val, minDp[i][j-1] * val)

minDp[i][j] = min(same four candidates)
Final answer:

If maxDp[m-1][n-1] < 0 → return -1
Else → return maxDp[m-1][n-1] % (10^9 + 7)


⚠️ Apply MOD only at the very end, not during DP — because mod breaks comparison logic.


